verses.text:
I wish that I had died when I was born;
\q2 I wish I had perished when I came out from my mother's womb.
\q1

After wicked people die, they do not cause any more troubles;
\q2 those who are very tired now will rest.
\q1

Those who were in prison rest peacefully after they die;
\q2 they no longer have slave drivers who curse them.
\q1

I cry very much; as a result, I cannot eat;
\q2 I groan as easily as a river flows with water.
\q1

Things that I always worried might happen to meâ€”these things have happened to me;
\q2 things that I always dreaded have come upon me.
\q1

Now I have no peace in my heart;
\q2 I have no quietness;
\q1 I cannot rest;
\q2 instead, I have only troubles."

In the past, when you spoke to others who were suffering, you helped them;
\q2 they were able to rejoice again because of God.
\q1

I have seen this happen: if farmers plant bad seeds, they do not harvest good crops;
\q2 anyone who starts trouble for others later brings trouble on himself.
\q1

It caused me to be afraid and tremble;
\q2 it caused all my bones to shake.
\q1

God cannot be sure that his own angels will always do what is right;
\q2 he declares that some of them have done wrong.
\q1

Foolish people die because they are resentful;
\q2 people whom others easily deceiveâ€”these people die because they envy others.
\q1

But it is not the farmland that makes bad things happen;
\q2 troubles do not grow up from the ground like plants.
\q1

He does great things, things that we cannot understand;
\q2 we cannot even count the marvelous things that he does.
\q1

He sends rain on the ground;
\q2 he makes it rain on our fields.
\q1

The people who think they are wiseâ€”he makes their own traps catch them;
\q2 the result is that they do not succeed.
\q1

But God saves helpless people from the wicked who say evil things about them;
\q2 he saves poor people from powerful people harming them.
\q1

But those whom God corrects are fortunate;
\q2 so do not despise it when God, who can do anything, disciplines you.
\q1

He wounds people, but then he puts bandages on those wounds;
\q2 he hurts people, but he also heals them.
\q1

God will protect you when people say false, evil things about you;
\q2 you will not be afraid when many things around you perish.
\q1

You will know that things will go well for you in your home;
\q2 when you look at your livestock, you will see that they are all there.
\q1

Answer me now, and then I will be quiet;
\q2 tell me what wrong things I have done!
\q1

"People need to work hard on this earth like soldiers do;
\q1 all during the time that we are alive, we need to work as hard as any hired worker.
\q1

God has given to me many months in which I think that it is useless to remain alive;
\q1 he has assigned to me many nights during which I feel miserable.
\q1

My days pass as quickly as a weaver's shuttle;
\q2 when one day ends, I never expect that things will be better the next day.
\q1

God, do not forget that my life is as short as a single breath;
\q2 I think that I will never again experience being happy.
\q1

Like a cloud passes and disappears,
\q2 people die and descend to the place where dead people are, and they do not return;
\q1

So I will not be silent;
\q2 while I am suffering, I will speak;
\q1 I will complain to God about what has happened to me
\q2 because I am very angry.
\q1

When I lie down at night, I say to myself, 'I will go to sleep and stop suffering;
\q2 my pain will be less while I am sleeping.'
\q1

But then you give me dreams that cause me to be afraid;
\q2 you give me visions that terrify me;
\q1

We human beings are not very important;
\q2 so why do you pay so much attention to us ?
\q1

Your children have sinned against him;
\q2 this is evident because he has punished them for those evil things.
\q1

Papyrus certainly does not grow away from marshland;
\q2 reeds certainly cannot grow where there is no water.
\q1

Those who do not pay attention to what God says are like those reeds;
\q2 godless people stop confidently expecting that good things will happen to them.
\q1

The things they confidently expect to happen do not happen;
\q2 things they trust will help them are as weak as a spider's web.
\q1

If they lean against a house, it falls on them;
\q2 if they cling to things for safety, those things will not remain firm.
\q1

God is very wise and powerful;
\q2 no one who has tried to argue against him has ever been able to win.
\q1

He sends earthquakes that shake the ground;
\q2 he causes the columns that support the earth to shake.
\q1

He alone stretched [stretches] out the sky;
\q2 he alone puts his feet on the waves and stops their violence.
\q1

He does great things that we cannot understand;
\q2 he does more marvelous things than we are able to count.
\q1

He passes by where I am, but I cannot see him;
\q2 he moves further on, but I do not see him go.
\q1

If he wants to snatch someone away, no one could stop him;
\q2 no one dares ask him, 'Why are you doing that?' 
\q1

My days pass very quickly, like a fast runner who passes one by;
\q2 it is as though the days run away, and nothing good ever happens to me.
\q1

If I smile and say to God, 'I will forget what I am complaining about;
\q2 I will stop looking sad and try to be cheerful,'
\q1

I will say to God, 'Do not just say that you must punish me;
\q2 in addition, tell me what wrong you saw that I have done.
\q1

Do not forget that you made me from a piece of clay;
\q2 are you going to cause me to become soil again?
\q1

But you kept secret what you were planning to do to me;
\q2 I am certain that you were planning to do these things to me.
\q1

I think that there are only a few days for me to remain alive;
\q2 so allow me to be alone, in order that I may have a little peace
\q1

You say, 'What I say is true;
\q2 God knows that I am innocent.'
\q1

What there is to know about God is greater than the distance from earth to heaven;
\q2 so there is no way that you can understand it all.
\q1 It is greater than the distance from here to the place of the dead;
\q2 so it is impossible for you to know it all.
\q1

He knows which people are worthless;
\q2 and when he sees people doing wicked things, he certainly does not ignore them.
\q1

Job, repent and make your heart humble;
\q2 reach out your hands toward God and plead with him.
\q1

If you have done evil things, stop doing them;
\q2 and do not allow any people in your house to do wicked deeds.
\q1

If you do that, surely you will be able to carry your head high, because you will not be ashamed;
\q2 you will be strong and not afraid of anything.
\q1

You will forget all your troubles;
\q2 they will be like the water that has all flowed away and dried up.
\q1

Your troubles will be ended, like the darkness ends at the dawn;
\q2 it will be as though the sun were shining brightly on you, like it shines at noon.
\q1

You will feel safe, because you will be confident that good things will happen to you;
\q2 God will protect you and allow you to rest safely each night.
\q1

But wicked people will not be able to understand why bad things are happening to them;
\q2 they will not have any way to escape from their troubles.
\q2 The only thing that they will want to do is to die. "

It is easy for people like you, who have no troubles, to laugh at people like me;
\q2 you make us who are already suffering to have even more troubles.
\q1

He directs the lives of all living creatures;
\q2 he gives breath to all us humans to enable us to live.
\q1

Old people are usually very wise;
\q2 because they have lived a long time, they understand much.
\q1

And God is wise and very powerful;
\q2 he has good sense and understands everything.
\q1

If he tears something down, no one can rebuild it;
\q2 if he puts someone in prison, no one can open the door to let that person to escape.
\q1

He is the one who is truly strong and wise;
\q2 he rules over those who deceive others and those whom they deceive.
\q1

What you know, I also know;
\q2 I do not know less than you.
\q1

But I would like to speak with Almighty God, not with you;
\q2 I would like to argue with him and show him that I am innocent.
\q1

I wish that you would be silent;
\q2 that would be wiser than anything you have said to me.
\q1

Listen to what I will say to you now;
\q2 listen while I am saying what is true about myself.
\q1

You are telling lies to help God;
\q2 you are saying what is false in order to help him!
\q1

He will certainly bring the full force of his power against you;
\q2 you will become very afraid of him.
\q1

So be quiet and allow me to speak;
\q2 after that, it will not matter what happens to me.
\q1

I am ready to risk my life;
\q2 I am even willing to risk that God will execute me for what I say.
\q1

I am requesting you to do two things for me;
\q2 if you do them, I will not try to hide from you.
\q1

Speak first, and then I will reply;
\q2 or allow me to speak first, and then you reply.
\q1

"If you were truly wise, you would not have replied to us by claiming that you know a lot;
\q2 what you are saying is just a lot of hot air.
\q1

You should not be saying things that do not benefit anyone;
\q2 you should not say things that do no one any good.
\q1

You are wicked, and that is why you say what you do;
\q2 you talk like deceptive people talk.
\q1

God does not even trust his angels;
\q2 he does not consider the heavens to be completely pure.
\q1

(God gave this land to those ancestors who were truly wise;
\q2 no one from another country came and caused them to think wrongly about God.)
\q1

Wicked people suffer with great pain all the time that they are alive;
\q2 that is what happens to those who oppress others.
\q1

They constantly hear sounds that terrify them;
\q2 while they are prospering, robbers attack them.
\q1

Wicked people do not really think that they will escape from darkness;
\q2 they are sure that someone is waiting to kill them with a sword.
\q1

While they are still young, they will disappear;
\q2 they will be like branches that wither and never become green again.
\q1

"I have heard things like that before;
\q2 all of you, instead of helping me, are only causing me to feel more miserable.
\q1

God, you have now taken away all my strength;
\q2 you have destroyed all my family.
\q1

Previously, I was living peacefully,
\q2 but he crushed me;
\q1 it is as though he grabbed my neck and smashed me to pieces;
\q2 it is as though he set me up like a target.
\q1

"My time to live is almost ended; I have no strength left;
\q2 those who have dug my grave are waiting for me.
\q1

Those who are around me are making fun of me;
\q2 I must always see them mocking me."
\q1

But now people use that saying of our ancestors when they talk about me;
\q2 they spit to insult me.
\q1

People who are truly righteous will be shocked when they see what has happened to me;
\q2 they will be angry at those who refuse to honor God.
\q1

My friends do not know when it is night and when it is day;
\q2 when it is night, they claim that it is daylight;
\q2 when it is becoming dark, they claim that it is getting light.
\q1

Everywhere they go, there will be things that cause them to be terrified;
\q2 it will be as though those things were pursuing them and biting at their heels.
\q1

Diseases will spread all over their skin;
\q2 diseases will cause their bodies to decay.
\q1

No one on the earth will remember them anymore;
\q2 no one on any street will even remember their names.
\q1

You have insulted me many times;
\q2 are you not ashamed for saying these things to me?
\q1

He has taken away my good reputation;
\q2 it is as though he has removed a crown from my head.
\q1

He attacks me because he is very angry at me;
\q2 he considers me to be his enemy.
\q1

When I summon my servants, they do not answer;
\q2 When I plead with them to come to help me, they do not come.
\q1

Even young children despise me;
\q2 when I stand up to talk to them, they laugh at me.
\q1

you should fear that God will punish you;
\q1 he punishes those like you with whom he is angry;
\q2 and when that happens, you will know that there is someone who judges people."

Those people who now see those wicked people will never see them again;
\q2 even the people who lived with them will not see them anymore.
\q1

Doing evil deeds is like swallowing snake poison;
\q2 doing evil will kill the wicked as the bite of a poisonous snake will kill people.
\q1

When they finished eating their food, there was never anything left over because they had greedily eaten it all;
\q2 but now their prosperity will end.
\q1

"Listen to what I say, all of you;
\q2 that is the only thing that you can do that will comfort me.
\q1

While they are alive, they say to God, 'Leave us alone;
\q2 we do not care about how you desire us to conduct our lives!
\q1

He does not blow them away as wind blows away straw;
\q2 they are never carried off by a whirlwind.
\q1

Their bodies are fat;
\q2 their bones are strong.
\q1

Other people die being very miserable;
\q2 they have never experienced good things happening to them.
\q1

that wicked people usually do not suffer at the time when there are great disasters;
\q2 that when God punishes people, someone rescues the wicked? that wicked people are the ones whom someone else rescues when God punishes people?
\q1

You must have lent money to others and wrongly forced them to give you things to guarantee that they would pay that money back to you;
\q2 you must have taken all their clothes and left them with nothing to wear.
\q1

Because you did all those things, now there are traps that will catch you;
\q2 now things appear that terrify you and cause you to tremble.
\q1

They suddenly died while they were still young;
\q2 they disappeared like everything disappears when there is a flood .
\q1

So, Job, be reconciled to God and make peace with him;
\q2 if you do that, good things will happen to you.
\q1

If you humble yourself and return to God, he will restore you;
\q2 if you stop doing all the evil things that you have been doing in your house,
\q1

You will pray to him, and he will do what you request him to do;
\q2 you will do the things that you promised him that you would do.
\q1

Everything that you decide to do will be successful;
\q2 it will be as though a light were shining on the road in front of you.
\q1

"Today I am again complaining bitterly to God;
\q2 I continue to groan, but I suffer even more.
\q1

If I could do that, I would tell him why I know that I am innocent;
\q2 I would tell him many reasons for that.
\q1

However, I have gone to the east, and he is not there;
\q2 I have gone to the west, but I have not found him there.
\q1

he knows how I have conducted my life;
\q2 when he has finished testing me, he will see that I am as pure as gold whose impurities have all been burned out.
\q1

I have faithfully walked on the road that he showed me;
\q2 I have not turned away from obeying him.
\q1

So I am terrified when I am in front of him;
\q2 when I think about what he can do, I am very afraid.
\q1

Some evil people remove the boundary markers of other people's land, in order to take their land;
\q2 they seize other people's sheep and put them in their own pastures.
\q1

Some evil men snatch poor, fatherless infants away from their mothers;
\q2 they say 'I will return your babies to you when you repay the money that I lent to you.'
\q1

But the poor people walk around with no clothes on;
\q2 they are hungry while they are working to carry other people's bundles of grain to the places where their grain will be threshed.
\q1

Some wicked people avoid the light because they do evil things in the dark;
\q2 they do not walk on roads that are lit.
\q1

Those who want to commit adultery wait for evening to come;
\q2 they say, 'I do not want anyone to see me,' so they keep their faces covered.
\q1

The wicked mistreat women who have been unable to give birth to children who would have grown up to take care of them;
\q2 the wicked they never help widows.
\q1

They prosper for a little while,
\q2 and then suddenly they are gone;
\q2 God will make them die like all the other people;
\q2 they will be like stalks of grain that the farmers have cut off.
\q1

"God is very powerful; everyone should honor him very much;
\q2 he causes everything to be peaceful high up in heaven, with no confusion at all.
\q1

"I am a very weak and helpless man;
\q2 you do not really think that you have helped me at all, do you?
\q1

God knows all about those who are in the place of the dead;
\q2 there is nothing down there that prevents God from seeing what is there.
\q1

By his power he calmed the sea;
\q2 by his skill he destroyed Rahab, the huge sea monster.
\q1

By his breath he caused the sky to be bright;
\q2 by his hand he killed the great dragon in the sea as it was fleeing from him.
\q1

But those events show only a small amount of his power;
\q2 it is as though we were hearing only whispers of his powerful voice.
\q2 When we hear thunder, we say, 'Who can really understand how great his power is?'"

I will not lie;
\q2 I will not say anything to deceive anyone.
\q1

I will never admit that what you three have said is true;
\q2 until the day that I die, I will insist that I have not done things that are wrong.
\q1

I want God to punish my enemies like he will punish all wicked people;
\q2 I want him to punish those who oppose me like he punishes all unrighteous people.
\q1

I will teach you three something about God's power;
\q2 I will reveal to you what he is thinking.
\q1

The houses that they build are as weak as spider webs;
\q2 they are like flimsy huts that watchmen live in while they guard people's fields.
\q1

Things that terrify them come to them like a flood that they do not expect;
\q2 during the night a whirlwind carries them away.
\q1

Miners dig very hard rock;
\q2 it is as though they turned the mountains upside down to get the ore.
\q1

Humans do not know what wisdom is truly worth;
\q2 no one can find it here on this earth where they are living.
\q1

Wisdom is worth more than coral or crystal quartz;
\q2 the price of wisdom is higher than the price of rubies.
\q1

No living humans can see it;
\q2 and birds cannot see it while they are up in the sky.
\q1

God is the only one who knows how to find wisdom;
\q2 he knows where it is
\q1

because he can see things even in the most remote places on the earth;
\q2 he can see everything that is below the sky.
\q1

I always acted justly;
\q2 my actions were like a robe that I wore and like a turban that was wrapped around my head.
\q1

When I spoke, people waited to hear what I would say;
\q2 they remained silent until I advised them what they should do.
\q1

After I finished speaking, they did not say anymore;
\q2 it was as though my words fell on their ears like drops of rain.
\q1

They waited for me to speak as they wait for rain;
\q2 they liked what I said as farmers appreciate the final rain in the spring before the dry season.
\q1

When they were sad, I smiled at them to encourage them;
\q2 they became encouraged when they saw my cheerful face.
\q1

I was their leader, and I decided what things would be good for them to do;
\q2 I was among them like a king who is among his troops;
\q2 I was like someone who comforts others who are mourning."

They were men who were old and weak;
\q2 what could I gain from having these men work for me, even when they thought they were strong?
\q1

They pulled up plants in the desert and ate them;
\q2 they warmed themselves by burning the roots of broom trees.
\q1

Gangs of these people attack me and force me to run away;
\q2 they prepare to destroy me.
\q1

Now I am about to die;
\q2 I suffer every day.
\q1

I cry out to you, God, but you do not answer me;
\q2 I stand up and pray, but you do not pay any attention.
\q1

You act very cruelly toward me;
\q2 with all of your power you cause me to suffer.
\q1

You allow the wind to lift me up and blow me away;
\q2 and you make a violent storm blow me around.
\q1

However, when I expected good things to happen to me, evil things happened;
\q2 when I waited for light, I experienced darkness instead.
\q1

I am very distressed all the time;
\q2 I suffer every day.
\q1

I go about very discouraged;
\q2 I stand up and plead for people to help me.
\q1

I request only that God judge me fairly;
\q2 if he does that, he will know that I am innocent.
\q1

or if it is true that I threatened to strike any orphan
\q2 because I knew that the elders at the city gates would approve of me;
\q1

29-30 It is not true that I sinned by requesting God to curse people who hated me
\q2 and to cause them to die;
\q1 or that I was glad when they were ruined
\q2 and rejoiced when they experienced disasters;
\q1

Some people try to hide their sins,
\q2 but I have never done that;
\q1

If it is true that I have stolen land,
\q2 so that its furrows were like someone who shouted out to accuse me;
\q1

I tell myself this: these three men are confused because they have nothing more to say to Job;
\q2 they have nothing more to say to him.
\q1

But because you do not speak, I certainly will not wait any longer;
\q2 you merely stand there and do not reply anymore.
\q1

I must speak in order that I can rest from trying to hold in my words;
\q2 I must say something to reply to you all.
\q1

God considers that you and I are both the same;
\q2 he formed both of us from clay.
\q1

So you do not need to be afraid of me;
\q2 I will not speak against you harshly.
\q1

'I am innocent, and I have not committed any sins;
\q2 I am pure, and I have not done things that are wrong.
\q1

He reveals things to us in those times;
\q2 he terrifies us by warning us about things.
\q1

He does not want us to be destroyed;
\q2 he wants to prevent us from dying while we are still young.
\q1

Please let his body be strong again;
\q2 please allow him to be strong like he was when he was young!'
\q1

So Job, listen to me;
\q2 do not say anything more; just allow me to speak.
\q1

"You men who think that you are very wise, listen to me;
\q2 listen to what I am saying, you men who say that you know so much.
\q1

He pays back people for what they have done;
\q2 he gives them what they deserve for the way that they have conducted their lives.
\q1

Truly, Almighty God never does what is wicked;
\q2 he never calls wrongdoing right.
\q1

They often die suddenly;
\q2 he strikes them at midnight and they die;
\q2 he gets rid of important people without the help of any humans.
\b
\q1

He sees everything that people do;
\q2 when we walk, he watches every step that we take.
\q1

He strikes them because of the wicked things that they have done;
\q2 many people see him do it.
\q1

Job, have you or anyone else ever said to God, 'I have certainly committed sin,
\q2 but I will not sin anymore;
\q1

'Job is speaking ignorantly;
\q2 what he says is nonsense.'
\q1

To add to the other sins that he has committed, he is rebelling against God;
\q2 he shows us that he does not honor God;
\q2 he makes long speeches saying that God has punished him unjustly."

People cry out because of the many things that others do to make them suffer;
\q2 they call for help because of the things that powerful people do to them.
\q1

He should be able to teach us more than he teaches the wild animals;
\q2 he should enable us to become wiser than all the birds are!'
\q1

However, now he is punishing you as he would punish the wicked;
\q2 God has judged you very rightly.
\q1

If that happens, it certainly will not help you to cry out when you are distressed;
\q2 none of your strength will help you in that case.
\q1

Do not wish that it would be nighttime in order that you might mistreat others without anyone knowing it;
\q2 night is the time when even entire people groups are destroyed!
\q1

Truly, people praise God because he is so powerful;
\q2 there is certainly no teacher who teaches what he teaches.
\q1

He draws water up from the earth and puts it in clouds
\q2 and causes it to become rain;
\q1

When God speaks, it causes us to fear him and admire him, as thunder does;
\q2 he does amazing things that we cannot understand.
\q1

Job, listen to this;
\q2 stop and think about the wonderful things that God does.
\q1

Only God knows everything perfectly;
\q2 so do you know how he causes the clouds to move in the sky?
\q1

No, you just sweat there in your clothes;
\q2 it is very oppressive when the hot wind stops blowing from the south and all the leaves on the trees become still.
\q1

Job, you know so much! So tell us what we should say to God;
\q2 we do not know anything about how we should defend ourselves.
\q1

God comes out of the north with a light that shines like gold;
\q2 his glory causes us to be afraid.
\q1

They do not like the noise in the cities;
\q2 in the desert they do not have to listen to the shouts of those who forced them to work.
\q1

The horses run very quickly, and they speedily cover the ground;
\q2 they rush into battle as soon as the trumpet is blown.
\q1

After an eagle kills an animal,
\q2 the baby eagles drink the blood of that animal;
\q2 they gather wherever there are dead people lying on the ground."

Show that you are very angry;
\q2 show that you have the right to humble people who are very proud!
\q1

They lie down in the water under the lotus plants;
\q2 they hide in tall reeds in the swamps.
\q1

They are not disturbed by raging, flooding rivers;
\q2 they are not even disturbed when rivers like the Jordan River rush over them.
\q1

The scales are very close together;
\q2 not even air can get between them.
\q1

Their necks are very strong;
\q2 wherever they go, they make people very afraid.
\q1

People cannot injure them with swords;
\q2 spears, arrows, or or other weapons with sharp points cannot injure them, either.
\q1
